<font color="#FF0000">MY THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 27 22:28:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To John,<br>
My reference to wasted was not meant in any way to detract the service these men and women provided.  They laid their lives down fighting for country and fighting for us.  I like to think that every person who died for this country are responsible for my freedom today, the very freedom that allows me to express my views in a free society.  Their service is never wasted.  My reference to &quot;wasted&quot; is to express what I consider a wasted talent.  What could these men and women have taught us?  What could these people have done in society?  I watched the Memorial Day celebration on PBS with my dad over the weekend, and they featured a women who lost her husband.  He left two daughters, one three and one born a day after he died who never knew him (Their story is on that Vietnam Veterans website).  His effort and sacrifice for this country IS NEVER WASTED, but his talent and knowledge is gone forever.  Imagine what he could have taught his daughters or explained to others.  My use of the term &quot;wasted&quot; is to express how war can destroy people that could have done God knows what for society.<br><br>
I understand your view on how a effort or loss of life may be pivitol 75 years in the future, beyond the scope of our lives, and I 100% totally agree with you.  Wars and sacrifice have made a difference, look at World War II and all the people freed.  The war cost many lives, but Europe and Japan are free and doing well.  One hope is that wars or fights of any kind are well planned and thought out before they begin.  The price of freedom is never cheap, but that does not make it the loss any easier to accept.<br><br>
My view and feelings of this topic comes from my trip to the wall in Washington DC (have visited it 3 times since-trying to get my dad to go).  I stood their examining all those names, looking up ones my father and mother talked about.  It just was way too much for me.  What really got me were the pictures of guys my age (23) that were killed left at the bottom of the wall.  I deeply appreciate their loss, they fought for each other and for their country and indirectly for me.  Their lives were not wasted, but their talents were.  I view life as a pond and each person makes a ripple in it, like a stone, with each life touching another.  I can't help but think about these men.  Vets like you or my father knew some of them, but I don't.  What could these men have become or what might their children have done?  I just hope any soldier's sacrifice is enough to make a difference, something that means enough to be equal to the talent we as a whole have lost by their passing.  Sorry to ramble on here, but I don't want anyone to misunderstand me or think of me as ungrateful or insensitive.<br><br>
Hey Doc Del-it is a very poor teacher indeed that can't take a few minutes to talk about our vets and their sacrifices.  Kids understand more than what we give them credit for.  Their natural curiosity needs to be fed.  I always try to talk about our vets and their sacrifices with any students I've had.  When I taught sixth grade, we honored Veterans Day with poems and a discussion on the role of vets and what they have done for this country.  I like to make it personal by having students find out about the vets in their family, and evening posting the names of the men and women killed from our local area.  I once heard a second grader ask a Marine recruiter who came to the elementary school to explain the importance of our soldiers the following question, &quot;If people always die in war or get hurt, why do young people still join the military today knowing they could die or get hurt?&quot;  I have never forgotten that question-a profound question from a little child.  Children understand a lot more tan we sometimes give them credit for!!  They deserve answers.  I hope you daughter has learned what she sought.<br><br>
In regards to Memorial Day Doc Del, perhaps it is a day for the living.  Our vets should be happy to be alive, living lives their buddies couldn't, perhaps even borrowed time.  I would imagine living life the best you can and remembering the men who didn't come back is the best tribute.  I would imagine any guy on that wall, would love to go fishing with you or any other of the fine vets here (I say this with the highest respect).  After all they have found peace, its us the living who need to seek a reason or peace of mind, so maybe this holiday is really for us too.<br><br>
Well I better stop here, before the PBS people flip out for filling up their site.  Thanks for listening to me guys.<br>
 
